\subsection{Multi-Concept and Dual-Concept Erasure}
\label{subsec:multi_results}

Beyond nudity, \ours{} generalizes to other unsafe concepts without concept-specific training---only the exemplar prompts and keywords change. Table~\ref{table:multi} reports MJA per-concept SR; Table~\ref{table:dual} reports simultaneous dual-concept erasure.

\input{table/multi_concept}

Reporting both modes exposes a complementary pattern: hybrid wins when the paired anchor is visually crisp---MJA-Sexual (86.0\%, $+38$\%p vs.\ SAFREE) and MJA-Disturbing (99.0\%, $+4$\%p)---while anchor inpainting wins on MJA-Violent (56.0\%, $+4$\%p), where ``peaceful scene'' is an ambiguous anchor and hybrid's chase-the-anchor objective becomes unstable (hybrid 29.0\%). On MJA-Illegal, SAFREE (77.0\%) still edges both modes (anchor 56.0, hybrid 72.0); the concept is image-dominant (Appendix~\ref{app:probe_dominance}) but its anchors (\textit{drug use}$\to$\textit{legal activity}) lack a clean visual pair, a shared challenge for all training-free methods. \emph{Which} mode wins is concept-dependent, so we report both and leave the choice to the deployer.

\input{table/dual_concept}

With family-grouped packs as the default, Nudity~$+$~Shocking (Table~\ref{table:dual}) retains 83.7\% nudity SR and 97.5\% shocking SR---close to the single-concept references of 93.1\% and 97.3\%, i.e.\ little destructive interference. Because each concept is decomposed into $F$ semantically independent anchors, simultaneous suppression is routed per sub-category rather than through a collapsed direction, which makes family grouping particularly attractive for \emph{multi-concept} deployment. The remaining three pairs (Nudity~$+$~\{Violence, Harassment, Hate\}) and the full interference analysis are in Appendix~\ref{app:dual_pairs}, \ref{app:interference}.

